[src:multer-upload/api-file] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:multer-upload/api-file] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:multer-upload/api-file] The **`File`** interface provides information about files and allows JavaScript in a web page to access their content.
[src:multer-upload/api-file] `File` objects are generally retrieved from a `FileList` object returned as a result of a user selecting files using the `<input>` element, or from a drag and drop operation's `DataTransfer` object.
[src:multer-upload/api-file] A `File` object is a specific kind of `Blob`, and can be used in any context that a Blob can.
[src:multer-upload/api-file] See Using files from web applications for more information and examples.
[src:multer-upload/api-file] Returns the last modified time of the file, in millisecond since the UNIX epoch (January 1st, 1970 at Midnight).
[src:multer-upload/api-file] Returns the last modified `Date` of the file referenced by the `File` object.
[src:multer-upload/api-file] Returns the name of the file referenced by the `File` object.
[src:multer-upload/api-file] Returns the path the URL of the `File` is relative to.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] The **`FormData`** interface provides a way to construct a set of key/value pairs representing form fields and their values, which can be sent using the `fetch()`, `XMLHttpRequest.send()` or `navigator.sendBeacon()` methods.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] It uses the same format a form would use if the encoding type were set to `"multipart/form-data"`.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] You can also pass it directly to the `URLSearchParams` constructor if you want to generate query parameters in the way a `<form>` would do if it were using simple `GET` submission.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] An object implementing `FormData` can directly be used in a `for...of` structure, instead of `entries()`: `for (const p of myFormData)` is equivalent to `for (const p of myFormData.entries())`.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Appends a new value onto an existing key inside a `FormData` object, or adds the key if it does not already exist.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Deletes a key/value pair from a `FormData` object.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Returns an iterator that iterates through all key/value pairs contained in the `FormData`.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Returns the first value associated with a given key from within a `FormData` object.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Returns an array of all the values associated with a given key from within a `FormData`.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Returns whether a `FormData` object contains a certain key.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Returns an iterator iterates through all keys of the key/value pairs contained in the `FormData`.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Sets a new value for an existing key inside a `FormData` object, or adds the key/value if it does not already exist.
[src:multer-upload/api-formdata] Returns an iterator that iterates through all values contained in the `FormData`.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] The original author, TJ Holowaychuk, described it as a Sinatra-inspired server, meaning that it is relatively minimal with many features available as plugins.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] Express is the back-end component of popular development stacks like the MEAN, MERN or MEVN stack, together with the MongoDB database software and a JavaScript front-end framework or library.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] Express.js was founded by TJ Holowaychuk.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] The initial versions were created in early 2010, and milestone version 1 was released later that year.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] In June 2014, rights to manage the project were acquired by StrongLoop.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] StrongLoop was acquired by IBM in September 2015; in January 2016, IBM announced that it would place Express.js under the stewardship of the Node.js Foundation incubator.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] In July 2014, work began towards milestone version 5.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] After ten years of development it was released in October 2024.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] Express.js is used by Fox Sports, PayPal, Uber and IBM.
[src:multer-upload/express-js] The following program will respond to HTTP GET requests with the text "Hi, your request has been received", and listen to the port the program is running on (in this case, port 2000).
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Multer is a node.js middleware for handling `multipart/form-data`, which is primarily used for uploading files.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] It is written on top of busboy for maximum efficiency.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Multer adds a `body` object and a `file` or `files` object to the `request` object.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] The `body` object contains the values of the text fields of the form, the `file` or `files` object contains the files uploaded via the form.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Don't forget the `enctype="multipart/form-data"` in your form.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Here's an example on how multer is used in a HTML form.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Then in your javascript file you would add these lines to access both the file and the body.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] It is important that you use the `name` field value from the form in your upload function.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] This tells multer which field on the request it should look for the files in.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Multer accepts an options object, the most basic of which is the `dest` property, which tells Multer where to upload the files.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] In case you omit the options object, the files will be kept in memory and never written to disk.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] By default, Multer will rename the files so as to avoid naming conflicts.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] The renaming function can be customized according to your needs.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] The following are the options that can be passed to Multer.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] In an average web app, only `dest` might be required, and configured as shown in the following example.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] If you want more control over your uploads, you'll want to use the `storage` option instead of `dest`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Multer ships with storage engines `DiskStorage` and `MemoryStorage`; More engines are available from third parties.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Accept a single file with the name `fieldname`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] The single file will be stored in `req.file`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Accept an array of files, all with the name `fieldname`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Optionally error out if more than `maxCount` files are uploaded.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] The array of files will be stored in `req.files`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Accept a mix of files, specified by `fields`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] An object with arrays of files will be stored in `req.files`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] `fields` should be an array of objects with `name` and optionally a `maxCount`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] If any file upload is made, error with code "LIMIT_UNEXPECTED_FILE" will be issued.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Accepts all files that comes over the wire.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] An array of files will be stored in `req.files`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] The disk storage engine gives you full control on storing files to disk.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] There are two options available, `destination` and `filename`.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] They are both functions that determine where the file should be stored.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] `destination` is used to determine within which folder the uploaded files should be stored.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] This can also be given as a `string` (e.g.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] If no `destination` is given, the operating system's default directory for temporary files is used.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] `filename` is used to determine what the file should be named inside the folder.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] If no `filename` is given, each file will be given a random name that doesn't include any file extension.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Each function gets passed both the request (`req`) and some information about the file (`file`) to aid with the decision.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Note that `req.body` might not have been fully populated yet.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] It depends on the order that the client transmits fields and files to the server.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] The memory storage engine stores the files in memory as `Buffer` objects.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] When using memory storage, the file info will contain a field called `buffer` that contains the entire file.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] An object specifying the size limits of the following optional properties.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Multer passes this object into busboy directly, and the details of the properties can be found on busboy's page.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Specifying the limits can help protect your site against denial of service (DoS) attacks.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Set this to a function to control which files should be uploaded and which should be skipped.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] When encountering an error, Multer will delegate the error to Express.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] You can display a nice error page using the standard express way.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] If you want to catch errors specifically from Multer, you can call the middleware function by yourself.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] Also, if you want to catch only the Multer errors, you can use the `MulterError` class that is attached to the `multer` object itself (e.g.
[src:multer-upload/expressjs-multer] For information on how to build your own storage engine, see Multer Storage Engine.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Uploading directly contrasts with downloading, where data is *received* over a network.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] In the case of users uploading files over the internet, uploading is often slower than downloading as many internet service providers (ISPs) offer asymmetric connections, which offer more network bandwidth for downloading than uploading.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] To transfer something (such as data or files), from a computer or other digital device to the memory of another device (such as a larger or remote computer) especially via the internet.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Remote file sharing first came into fruition in January 1978, when Ward Christensen and Randy Suess, who were members of the Chicago Area Computer Hobbyists' Exchange (CACHE), created the Computerized Bulletin Board System (CBBS).
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] This used an early file transfer protocol (MODEM, later XMODEM) to send binary files via a hardware modem, accessible by another modem via a telephone number.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] In the following years, new protocols such as Kermit were released, until the File Transfer Protocol (FTP) was standardized 1985 (RFC 959).
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] FTP is based on TCP/IP and gave rise to many FTP clients, which, in turn, gave users all around the world access to the same standard network protocol to transfer data between devices.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] The transfer of data saw a significant increase in popularity after the release of the World Wide Web in 1991, which, for the first time, allowed users who were not computer hobbyists to easily share files, directly from their web browser over HTTP.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Transfers became more reliable with the launch of HTTP/1.1 in 1997 (RFC 2068), which gave users the option to resume downloads that were interrupted, for instance due to unreliable connections.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Before web browsers widely rolled out support, software programs like GetRight could be used to resume downloads.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Resuming uploads is not currently supported by HTTP, but can be added with the Tus open protocol for resumable file uploads, which layers resumability of uploads on top of existing HTTP connections.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Transmitting a local file to a remote system following the client–server model, e.g., a web browser transferring a video to a website, is called **client-to-server uploading**.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Transferring data from one remote system to another remote system under the control of a local system is called **remote uploading** or site-to-site transferring.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] This is used when a local computer has a slow connection to the remote systems, but these systems have a fast connection between them.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Without remote uploading functionality, the data would have to first be downloaded to the local system and then uploaded to the remote server, both times over a slower connection.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Remote uploading is used by some online file hosting services.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Another example can be found in FTP clients, which often support the File eXchange Protocol (FXP) in order to instruct two FTP servers with high-speed connections to exchange files.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] A web-based example is the Uppy file uploader that can transfer files from a user's cloud storage such as Dropbox, directly to a website without first going to the user's device.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] The rising popularity of file sharing during the 1990s culminated in the emergence of Napster, a music-sharing platform specialized in MP3 files that used peer-to-peer (P2P) file-sharing technology to allow users exchange files freely.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] The P2P nature meant there was no central gatekeeper for the content, which eventually led to the widespread availability of copyrighted material through Napster.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] The Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA) took notice of Napster's ability to distribute copyrighted music among its user base, and, on December 6, 1999, filed a motion for a preliminary injunction in order to stop the exchange of copyrighted songs on the service.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] After a failed appeal by Napster, the injunction was granted on March 5, 2001.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] On September 24, 2001, Napster, which had already shut down its entire network two months earlier, agreed to pay a $26 million dollar settlement.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] After Napster had ceased operations, many other P2P file-sharing services also shut down, such as Limewire, Kazaa and Popcorn Time.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] Besides software programs, there were many BitTorrent websites that allowed files to be indexed and searched.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] These files could then be downloaded via a BitTorrent client.
[src:multer-upload/file-upload] While the BitTorrent protocol itself is legal and agnostic of the type of content shared, many of the services that did not enforce a strict policy to take down copyrighted material would eventually also run into legal difficulties.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] In information and communications technology, a **media type**, **content type** or **MIME type** is a two-part identifier for file formats and content formats.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Their purpose is comparable to filename extensions and uniform type identifiers, in that they identify the intended data format.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] They are mainly used by technologies underpinning the Internet, and also used on Linux desktop systems.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) is the official authority for the standardization and publication of these classifications.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Media types are also used by other internet protocols such as HTTP, document file formats such as HTML, and the XDG specifications implemented by Linux desktop environments, for similar purposes.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Different internet standards or web standards bodies differ on the preferred term for this type of identifier.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The IANA and IETF use the term "media type", and consider the term "MIME type" to be obsolete, since media types have become used in contexts unrelated to email, such as HTTP.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] By contrast, the WHATWG continues to use the term "MIME type" and discourages use of the term "media type" as ambiguous, since it is used with a different meaning in connection with the CSS `@media` feature.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The HTTP response header for providing the media type is `Content-Type`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The W3C has used `ContentType` as an XML data-type name for a media type.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] XDG specifications implemented by Linux desktop environments continue to use the term "MIME type".
[src:multer-upload/media-type] A media type consists of a *type* and a *subtype*, which is further structured into a *tree*.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] As an example, an HTML file might be designated `text/html; charset=UTF-8`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] In this example, `text` is the type, `html` is the subtype, and `charset=UTF-8` is an optional parameter indicating the character encoding.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Types, subtypes, and parameter names are case-insensitive.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Parameter values are usually case-sensitive, but may be interpreted in a case-insensitive fashion depending on the intended use.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The "type" part defines the broad use of the media type.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] As of November 1996, the registered types were `application`, `audio`,`image`, `message`, `multipart`, `text` and `video`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] By July 2024, the registered types included the foregoing, plus `font`, `example`, `model`, and `haptics`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] An unofficial top-level type in common use is `chemical`, used for chemical file formats.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] A subtype typically consists of a media format, but it may or must also contain other content, such as a tree prefix, producer, product or suffix, according to the different rules in registration trees.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] All media types should be registered using the IANA registration procedures.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] For the efficiency and flexibility of the media type registration process, different structures of subtypes can be registered in registration trees that are distinguished by the use of tree prefixes.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Currently, the following trees are created: standard (no prefix), vendor (`vnd.` prefix), personal or vanity (`prs.` prefix), unregistered (`x.` prefix).
[src:multer-upload/media-type] These registration trees were first defined in November 1996 (obsoleted RFC 2048 - currently RFC 6838).
[src:multer-upload/media-type] New registration trees may be created by IETF Standards Action for external registration and management by well-known permanent organizations (e.g. scientific societies).
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The standards tree does not use any tree prefix.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Examples are `text/javascript`, `image/png`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Registrations in the standards tree must be either associated with IETF specifications approved directly by the IESG, or registered by an IANA recognized standards-related organization.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The vendor tree includes media types associated with publicly available products.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Examples are: `application/vnd.ms-excel`, `application/vnd.oasis.opendocument.text`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The terms "vendor" and "producer" are considered equivalent in the context.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Industry consortia as well as non-commercial entities can register media types in the vendor tree.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] A registration in the vendor tree may be created by anyone who needs to interchange files associated with some software product or set of products.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] However, the registration belongs to the vendor or organization producing the software that employs the type being registered, and that vendor or organization can at any time elect to assert ownership of a registration done by a third party.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The personal or vanity tree includes media types associated with non publicly available products or experimental media types.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Examples are `audio/prs.sid`, `image/prs.btif`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The unregistered tree includes media types intended exclusively for use in private environments and only with the active agreement of the parties exchanging them.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Examples are `application/x.foo`, `video/x.bar`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Media types in this tree cannot be registered.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] This type was originally defined in RFC 1590 (published in September 1993) using the `x-` or `X-` prefix.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] RFC 2048 (published in November 1996) introduced the `x.` prefix, but discouraged use of the unregistered tree, as new personal and vendor trees with relaxed registration requirements are now available.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The current RFC 6838 (published in January 2013) maintains the same recommendation, but subtypes prefixed with `x-` or `X-` are no longer considered to be members of this tree.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Media types that have been widely deployed (with a subtype prefixed with `x-` or `X-`) without being registered, should be, if possible, re-registered with a proper prefixed subtype.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] If this is not possible, the media type can, after an approval by both the media types reviewer and the IESG, be registered in the standards tree with its unprefixed subtype.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` is an example of a widely deployed type that ended up registered with the `x-` prefix.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Suffix is an augmentation to the media type definition to additionally specify the underlying structure of that media type, allowing for generic processing based on that structure and independent of the exact type's particular semantics.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Media types that make use of a named structured syntax should use the appropriate IANA registered `"+"suffix` for that structured syntax when they are registered.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Unregistered suffixes should not be used (since January 2013).
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Structured syntax suffix registration procedures are defined in RFC 6838.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The +xml suffix has been defined since January 2001 (RFC 3023), and was formally included in the initial contents of the Structured Syntax Suffix Registry along with `+json`, `+ber`, `+der`, `+fastinfoset`, `+wbxml`, and `+zip` in January 2013 (RFC 6839).
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Subsequent additions include `+gzip`, `+cbor`, `+json-seq`, and `+cbor-seq`.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Mailcap (derived from the phrase "mail capability") is a type of meta file used to configure how MIME-aware applications such as mail clients and web browsers render files of different MIME-types.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] The mailcap format is defined by RFC 1524 "A User Agent Configuration Mechanism for Multimedia Mail Format Information" but is not defined as an Internet standard.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Lines can be comments starting with the # character, or a mime-type followed by how to handle that mime type.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] An associated file is the **mime.types** file, which associates filename extensions with a *MIME type*.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] If the MIME type is properly set, this is unnecessary, but MIME types may be incorrectly set, or set to a generic type such as `application/octet-stream`, and **mime.types** allows one to fall back on the extension in these cases.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] Similarly, since many file systems do not store MIME type information, but instead rely on the filename extension, a mime.types file is frequently used by web servers to determine MIME type.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] When *viewing* a file, these two work together as follows: **`mime.types`** associates an extension with a MIME type, while `mailcap` associates a MIME type with a program.
[src:multer-upload/media-type] In UNIX-type systems, the mime.types file is usually located at `/etc/**mime.types**` and/or `$HOME/**.mime.types**` and the format is simply that each line is a space-delimited list of a MIME type, followed by zero or more extensions.
